class Solution {
    public long maximumSubarraySum(int[] nums, int k) {
        long ans = Long.MIN_VALUE;
        long sum = 0;
        Map<Integer, Long> minS = new HashMap<>();
        for (int x : nums) {
            long s1 = sum - k;
            long s2 = minS.getOrDefault(x - k, Long.MAX_VALUE / 2);
            ans = Math.max(ans, sum - Math.min(s1, s2));
            minS.merge(x, sum, Math::min);
            sum += x;
        }
        return ans > Long.MIN_VALUE / 4 ? ans : 0;
    }
}

The problem statement is asking us to find the maximum sum of a good subarray in a given integer array nums. A good subarray is defined as a subarray where the absolute difference between its first and last element is exactly k. If there is no such good subarray, we should return 0. 

In the solution, a variable ans is used to keep track of the maximum sum found so far. A map minS is used to keep track of the minimum sum of all subarrays ending at each index. A variable sum is used to keep track of the sum of the current subarray.

The sum of the current subarray is calculated by subtracting the minimum sum of all subarrays ending at the index x-k or a large value if there is no such subarray from the sum of the current subarray. The maximum sum is updated with the maximum of the current maximum sum and the sum calculated in the previous step. 

The minimum sum of all subarrays ending at the current index is updated with the minimum of the current minimum sum and the sum of the current subarray. The sum of the current subarray is updated by adding the current element to the sum. 

The final maximum sum of a good subarray is returned if it is greater than Long.MIN_VALUE / 4, otherwise 0 is returned.

