class Solution {
    public int minOrAfterOperations(int[] nums, int k) {
        int ans = 0;
        int mask = 0;
        for (int b = 29; b >= 0; b--) {
            mask |= 1 << b;
            int cnt = 0; 
            int and = -1;
            for (int x : nums) {
                and &= x & mask;
                if (and != 0) {
                    cnt++; 
                } else {
                    and = -1; 
                }
            }
            if (cnt > k) {
                ans |= (1 << b);
                mask ^= 1 << b;
            }
        }
        return ans;
    }
}
In this code, the outer loop is trying to set the bits in the answer from most significant to least significant, and the inner loop is trying to find a bit position where the number of operations needed to merge consecutive numbers is less than or equal to k. If it finds such a bit position, it sets the corresponding bit in the answer, else it continues with the next bit. At the end, the result will be the minimum possible value of the bitwise OR of the remaining elements of nums after performing k operations.
Correctness: It's correct because it tries to minimize the bitwise OR of the remaining elements by trying to minimize the number of operations needed to merge consecutive numbers. It starts from the most significant bit and tries to set it if it can be set without exceeding the k operations limit. If it can't be set, it continues with the next bit.
Complexity: The time complexity is O(n) because it traverses the array once in the inner loop and the outer loop runs for 30 times which is constant time. The space complexity is O(1) because it doesn't use any extra space.
Notes: It's bit manipulation problem, we need to try to minimize the result, so we try to set each bit from left to right, and in each bit, we try to see if we can set it without exceeding the k operations limit. If we can, we set it, otherwise, we move to the next bit.
Concept: bit manipulation.

