class Solution {
    public int minimumArrayLength(int[] nums) {
        int m = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        for (int x : nums) {
            m = Math.min(m, x);
        }

        for (int x : nums) {
            if (x % m > 0) {
                return 1;
            }
        }

        int cnt = 0;
        for (int x : nums) {
            if (x == m) {
                cnt++;
            }
        }
        return nums.length - cnt;
    }
}
```

The above code takes the minimum number in the array (m), checks if any other number in the array has a remainder when divided by m, if it does, it returns 1, because that means we can't remove any other numbers, as removing other numbers could result in the removal of m. Then it counts the number of times m appears in the array (cnt), and subtracts it from the original length of the array to get the minimum length of the array after removing all instances of m.

